From: nix-wasm <eric@codebutler.com>
Date: Thu, 25 Jun 2026 00:00:00 -0400
Subject: [PATCH] virtio_wasm: register a virtio-vsock device (VIRTIO_ID_VSOCK)

Register a virtio-vsock device on the wasm virtio transport so the stock
mainline virtio-vsock transport (net/vmw_vsock/virtio_transport.c,
CONFIG_VIRTIO_VSOCKETS riding CONFIG_VSOCKETS) provides a standard
AF_VSOCK socket channel between guest and host. This is the vsock piece
of the "everything is a virtio device" consolidation (issue #10, option
3): it gives the guest→host /Ctl desktop-control bridge (launch pc app,
clipboard, notify) a standard socket carrier instead of riding 9P as an
`aname` mount. The /Ctl protocol consumer lives downstream in pc; this
patch (+ runtime/virtio/vsock-device.js) lands only the transport
substrate — the kernel device registration and the host device model.

Device index follows the existing enum order (WL=0, ECHO=1, NET=2,
BLK=3, 9P_ROOT=4, 9P_NIXCACHE=5, CONSOLE=6), so VSOCK is index 7. The
index is pinned with an explicit `= 7` so it stays stable regardless of
which of the CONFIG-guarded earlier slots are built — the host side
(runtime/kernel-worker.js / runtime/kernel-host.js VW_DEV_VSOCK = 7) and
the kernel must agree on the index that selects the device in every
host-call. Guarded by IS_ENABLED(CONFIG_VIRTIO_VSOCKETS) so the enum slot
and the init call are a no-op when the stock virtio-vsock transport is
not built.

This patch is sequenced AFTER 0019 (virtio-console) and ANCHORS ITS
HUNKS ON THE CONSOLE BLOCK, inserting the vsock enum slot and init call
*after* VW_DEV_CONSOLE — so VW_DEV_CONSOLE keeps index 6 and VSOCK is 7.
The previous revision of this patch anchored on the 9P block (it was
authored against the pre-0019 tree), so under `patch`'s fuzzy matching it
landed the vsock slot BEFORE the console slot — pushing VW_DEV_CONSOLE to
index 8 and (via the fuzzed registration hunk) dropping the 9P_ROOT /
9P_NIXCACHE virtio_wasm_register() calls entirely. That silently broke
the 9P transport: `9pnet_virtio: no channels available for device
pcroot/nixcache`, so the pc VFS root and the /nix-cache binary cache
never mounted (a nix:true boot reached a shell but `nix` could not read
/nix-cache). kernel.nix now asserts the post-patch enum order + 9P
registration so a future re-fuzz fails the build loudly instead.

Mainline virtio_transport.c (the guest-side virtio-vsock driver) binds
three virtqueues — rx (q0), tx (q1), event (q2) — and reads the 64-bit
guest CID from config space (struct virtio_vsock_config { __le64
guest_cid; }). The host serves the guest CID (3, the first guest CID;
the host is CID 2 = VMADDR_CID_HOST) in config space and drives the vqs
per the virtio-vsock packet framing (struct virtio_vsock_hdr + payload)
in runtime/virtio/vsock-device.js. The kernel side here is just the
device registration — no custom vsock transport code, the stock driver
does the rest.

The default 64-entry virtqueue is left unchanged for vsock: virtio-vsock
posts one packet (a virtio_vsock_hdr + bounded payload) per descriptor
chain, never the 128-sg-entry msize-sized chains that forced the 9P ring
to 128 — so 64 is comfortably correct (it is what QEMU's virtio-vsock
uses by default).

Part of issue #10 (host<->guest bridge consolidation onto virtio) —
the vsock transport for /Ctl (option 3).
---
 drivers/virtio/virtio_wasm.c | 22 ++++++++++++++++++++++
 1 file changed, 22 insertions(+)

diff --git a/drivers/virtio/virtio_wasm.c b/drivers/virtio/virtio_wasm.c
index c0ffee123..d15eaf456 100644
--- a/drivers/virtio/virtio_wasm.c
+++ b/drivers/virtio/virtio_wasm.c
@@ -374,6 +374,16 @@ enum {
 #if IS_ENABLED(CONFIG_VIRTIO_CONSOLE)
 	VW_DEV_CONSOLE,		/* virtio-console: a guest TTY (stock virtio_console.c) */
 #endif
+#if IS_ENABLED(CONFIG_VIRTIO_VSOCKETS)
+	/*
+	 * virtio-vsock: AF_VSOCK socket channel for the /Ctl bridge (issue #10
+	 * option 3). Pinned to host index 7 (WL=0..9P_NIXCACHE=5, CONSOLE=6)
+	 * with an explicit value so it stays stable regardless of which
+	 * CONFIG-guarded earlier slots are built; the host (VW_DEV_VSOCK = 7)
+	 * must agree on this index.
+	 */
+	VW_DEV_VSOCK = 7,
+#endif
 	VW_DEV_COUNT,
 };

@@ -428,6 +438,18 @@ static int __init virtio_wasm_transport_init(void)
 	vw = virtio_wasm_register(VW_DEV_CONSOLE, VIRTIO_ID_CONSOLE);
 	if (IS_ERR(vw))
 		pr_warn("virtio_wasm: console register failed: %ld\n", PTR_ERR(vw));
 #endif
+
+#if IS_ENABLED(CONFIG_VIRTIO_VSOCKETS)
+	/*
+	 * virtio-vsock channel for the host /Ctl bridge (stock
+	 * net/vmw_vsock/virtio_transport.c). The host serves the guest CID in
+	 * config space and drives the rx/tx/event vqs per the virtio-vsock
+	 * packet framing (runtime/virtio/vsock-device.js).
+	 */
+	vw = virtio_wasm_register(VW_DEV_VSOCK, VIRTIO_ID_VSOCK);
+	if (IS_ERR(vw))
+		pr_warn("virtio_wasm: vsock register failed: %ld\n", PTR_ERR(vw));
+#endif

 	return 0;
 }
--
